\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Designing for effectiveness and inclusivity: The role of gender attributes
 in video-enabled agricultural extension campaigns
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Bjorn Van Campenhout, Els Lecoutere, and David J Spielman
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Decision making is often hampered by knowledge constraints, hence simply
 providing information often makes a big difference.
 At the same time, seemingly small design attributes of information campaigns—th
e way the information is delivered, who delivers the information, or who
 is targeted by the message—can result in significant differences in effectivene
ss and inclusivity.
 In the context of a video-enabled agricultural extension information campaign,
 this study assesses how changing the gender of the person who provides
 the information and the gender of the person who receives the information
 affects effectiveness and inclusivity of the campaign.
 Our study relies on a field experiment conducted among smallholder maize
 farmers in Uganda.
 Effectiveness is judged by household level changes in knowledge, adoption,
 productivity and welfare.
 Inclusivity is assessed by gender dis-aggregating outcomes and through
 the assessment of changes in intra-household decision-making.
 Our experimental design allows us to test a range of hypotheses related
 to intra-household cooperation and bargaining power, gender stereotypes
 in agricultural production, and gender homophily effects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Often, optimal decision making among poor people in developing countries
 is hampered by a lack of critical pieces of information, the inability
 to benefit from learning externalities 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "doi:10.1086/601447"

\end_inset

, failure to notice vital information 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "doi:10.1093/qje/qju015"

\end_inset

, or false beliefs and erroneous perceptions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "10.1257/app.3.1.1,doi:10.1162/qjec.2010.125.2.515"

\end_inset

.
 In many instances, information campaigns designed to address these information
 inefficiencies can lead to significant differences in decision-making 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "banerjee2011poor"

\end_inset

.
 In the context of agricultural technology adoption among smallholder farmers
 in developing countries, information inefficiencies are particularly important,
 as a lack of information about the existence, use, and profitability of
 modern inputs, improved technologies, and recommended management practices
 have been documented to be a major constraint to productivity growth, sustainab
le intensification, and food security 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "doi:10.1086/451461,jack2013market"

\end_inset

.
 As such, agricultural extension programs and advisory services—often provided
 as a public service—are viewed as necessary to improving agricultural outcomes,
 especially in developing countries.
 More recently, with new possibilities offered by information and communications
 technology (ICT), an abundance of pilot projects and commercial products
 have entered the market with a focus on revitalizing agricultural extension
 in developing countries 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Aker2011"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, not all information campaigns are equally successful, and seemingly
 small design attributes—the way information is delivered, who delivers
 the information, and who was targeted—can significantly influence effectiveness
 and inclusivity.
 This is also the case for agricultural advisory services, where outcomes
 are mixed at best, and gender differentiated 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "davis2008extension"

\end_inset

.
 A growing body of evidence also suggests that not all ICT-mediated extension
 approaches are equally effective in achieving outcomes such as increased
 rates of technology adoption, and higher crop yields of man and woman farmers,
 or improvements in household welfare and intra-household equity.
 This is partly due to the fact that most agronomic information campaigns
 ignore the existence of information asymmetries within smallholder farm
 households and the fact that these households are composed of multiple
 decision makers, each with their own preferences, skills and access to
 resources.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper explores the role and importance of gender-related attributes
 in designing successful agricultural extension information campaigns, focusing
 on (i) the gender of the recipient of the information (or gender composition
 of recipients of information), and (ii) the gender of the messenger providing
 the information (or gender composition of providers of information).
 We study the relative importance of these two design attributes through
 a randomized control trial (RCT) that takes the form of a 3 by 3 factorial
 experiment.
 A first factor corresponds to the gender of the recipient (or gender compositio
n of recipients) of the information, and has 3 levels: (i) the information
 is provided to the husband only within the household, (ii) the information
 is provided to the wife alone, or (iii) the information is given to the
 both husband and wife together.
 Orthogonal to this first factor, a second factor is placed, corresponding
 to the gender of the messenger (or gender composition of messengers) providing
 the information.
 Similar to the first factor, this second factor has 3 levels: (i) a man
 alone provides all the information, (ii) a woman alone provides all the
 information, or (iii) the information is provided by a couple (man and
 woman together).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The factorial design allows us to test a range of hypotheses grounded in
 different strands of the literature.
 First, in the context of cooperative versus non-cooperative household models,
 we test if reducing information asymmetries within the household increases
 household level outcomes and reduces intra-household inequality.
 Second, deriving from the same theoretical framework, we test if priming
 a cooperative approach to farming within the household also translates
 into more cooperation within the household.
 Third, borrowing from the literature on intra-household bargaining, we
 test if arming women with information increases women decision making in
 agriculture and outcomes on women managed plots.
 Fourth, quite a few recent studies underscore the importance of female
 role models to encourage entry of women in male dominated sectors, and
 we test if showing female role models engaged in maize production alters
 household level and individual outcomes.
 Finally, some studies suggest gender homophily effects in agricultural
 extension, where information that comes from someone with the same gender
 appears to be more effective.
 We test if matching the gender of the recipient of the information with
 the gender of the messenger leads to better outcomes then when gender of
 recipient and messenger differs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We work with 3,600 farm households sampled from a population of nuclear
 households cultivating maize across five districts of eastern Uganda
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A nuclear household is defined as a household containing both one male and
 one female member who take decisions as head of household either jointly
 or singly in their respective spheres of responsibility.
 It thus excludes single headed households or polygamous households.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Maize is a key crop in the region, and is important for both home consumption
 and as a source of income.
 However, yields are low compared to what is attainable, especially on women
 managed plots.
 Modern input use is very low, and farmers use traditional agronomic practices.
 Again, this is particularly the case on women managed plots.
 Furthermore, access to agricultural extension is limited, generally targeted
 to the man within the household, and most of the agricultural extension
 agents are male.
 Taken together, this suggests ample scope for increasing both household
 level and individual level outcomes by stimulating adoption through carefully
 designed agricultural extension information campaigns.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The information treatments are implemented as short videos, that are shown
 to participating households according to the experimental design.
 Corresponding to the first factor regarding the recipient of information,
 a video is shown to (i) only the male co-head within the household, (ii)
 only the female co-head within the household, or (iii) the male and female
 co-head together within the household.
 To implement the second factor, related to the gender of the person that
 provides the information, we essentially produced three versions of the
 video.
 These three videos are identical, except for the fact that, in the first
 version all the information is provided by a male farmer.
 In the second version of the video, the male actor is replaced by an actress
 who provides all the information.
 In the third version of the video, the information is given by a man and
 a woman together acting as a couple.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The video itself provides technical information related to maize cultivation,
 such as optimal spacing and seed rate, soil fertility management, and the
 importance of quality seed, among others.
 Some of this information is new, while other information is likely to be
 known but not actively applied.
 Apart from offering agronomic advice, the video also promotes a more commercial
 attitude towards maize growing, underscoring for instance the importance
 of investing now to gain more in the future.
 The message is packaged in an appealing story, brought by model farmers
 that explain how they also used to struggle with low yields but became
 successful farmers after embracing modern inputs and improved agronomic
 practices.
 In sum, the video is designed to change farmer behavior through awareness,
 skill, and aspirational channels.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Changes in efficiency at the household level as a result of the treatments
 is judged by changes in four different families of outcomes: knowledge,
 adoption of technologies and practices, productivity, and well-being.
 Knowledge is judged by a short quiz consisting of four multiple choice
 questions.
 Adoption is measured as the implementation of 10 different technologies
 or practices, such as for instance the use of recommended spacing and seed
 rate, inorganic fertilizer use, timely weeding, etc.
 Production outcomes are the quantity of maize produced and area under cultivati
on (combined in yield), and also a more subjective measure of production.
 Well-being is measured by consumption expenditure, standard food security
 questions, and subjective measures of relative well-being.
 To assess changes in inclusivity due to changing the gender related design
 features, knowledge, adoption and production is dis-aggregated by gender,
 and inquire about intra-household decision making.
 Outcomes within each family are summarized in a single index to guard against
 over-rejection of the null due to multiple comparison.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the farm household level, we find that providing information to farmers
 through short video messages increases their knowledge about modern inputs,
 improved technologies, and recommended practices.
 In addition, farm households that were exposed to the video are also more
 likely to adopt a range of inputs, technologies, and practices that feature
 in the video.
 We also find clear effects on production, with average maize yields 14
 percent higher than in control households.
 However, these results do not translate into greater well-being.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We further find that if the extension information is brought by a woman
 or a couple, men to take less unilateral decisions related to maize farming,
 possibly due to the fact that the assumption that maize is a male activity
 is called into question.
 Furthermore, we find that if women farmers are also involved in receiving
 extension information (either alone or as part of the couple), women co-head
 take more decisions and also adopt more technologies and practices on the
 plots they manage.
 However, this increase in adoption does not lead to higher productivity
 on women managed plots.
 This may be because women tend to adopt technologies or practices that
 are relatively cheap (such as weeding), whereas men tend to adopt more
 expensive technologies such as inorganic fertilizer.
 The effects on yields of the former are generally much smaller than the
 yield effects of the latter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our research design also allows us to explore the consequences of reducing
 information asymmetries within households by comparing outcomes of households
 where the information was given to only one of the spouses (either the
 man or the woman) to outcomes of households where the information was given
 to the couple.
 While we do not find differences in knowledge, indicating that, to some
 extent, information is shared between spouses, we see that reducing information
 asymmetries leads to more joint decision-making, more adoption on jointly
 managed plots, and increased productivity under joint management.
 Encouraging cooperation on the household farm, by showing couples cooperate
 in the video, leads to more joint decision making and increases adoption
 on jointly managed plots.
 Finally, our research suggests that women are more likely to adopt modern
 technologies and recommended agronomic practices on their plots if the
 information is delivered by a woman.
\end_layout

