\begin_layout Standard
Maize is especially important in eastern Uganda.
 We sampled from five districts in eastern Uganda known for their maize
 production: Bugiri, Mayuge, Iganga, Namayingo, and Namutumba.
 From this, we removed town councils and also two sub-counties that consisted
 of islands in lake Victoria.
 We used two-stage cluster sampling to obtain a representative sample of
 this population.
 In particular, we first selected parishes randomly, with probability weights
 proportional to the number of villages within each parish.
 In the selected parishes, all villages were included in the study.
 Within each village, we then listed all the households, from which we randomly
 sampled households to be included in the study.
 Outcomes within villages are likely to be correlated, for instance due
 to local weather conditions, or development programs that are implemented
 in certain areas.
 We therefore used the village as a blocking factor: in each village, we
 made sure all possible treatment combinations related two factors (plus
 control) were administered.
 The experimental design described above shows that the messenger and the
 recipient factor combine into nine different treatment combinations.
 Adding the control leads to 10 different households being selected in each
 village.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In eastern Uganda, there are two maize cropping seasons.
 For our study, we concentrated on the second maize-growing season of the
