\begin_layout Subsection*
Overall Impact of the Information Intervention
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To get an idea of the overall impact of our intervention, we start by comparing
 household level outcomes at endline between the households that were shown
 an agricultural extension information video (the treatment group) and household
s that were shown a placebo video that did not contain any agricultural
 related information (the control group).
 Note that, in the context of a factorial design, in this comparison, we
 can abstract from the two other factors.
 In other words, it does not matter what version of the video was shown
 and to whom within the household the video was shown.
 In other words, at the household level, we want to know if the video interventi
on worked, regardless of who the video was shown to within the household,
 or who provided the information within the video.
 As such, we can compare all the households in the control group to all
 the households in all of the 9 treatment combination cells together in
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Experimental-Design"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The experiment was set up to be powered to test particular hypotheses, hence
 a series of power calculations resulted in a different number of households
 in particular treatment cells.
 For instance, one of the most demanding hypotheses is the homophily hypothesis,
 for which only four treatment cells can be used, and so these four treatment
 cell have relatively larger sample sizes.
 As a result, a simple average over all treatment cells would weigh outcomes
 of larger cell more.
 We avoid this by comparing treatment and control in a regression framework,
 including the levels of the other two factors as controls.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fn:The-experiment-was"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We first test the impact of the video intervention on knowledge.
 This was done through a short quiz 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "feder2004acquisition,feder2004sending,masset2015does"

\end_inset

 consisting of four questions that were asked during the endline survey
 to each of the two spouses in the farm household separately - regardless
 of who was shown the video.
 For each question, three possible answers were read out to the respondent,
 who was then asked to indicate which answer he or she though was correct.
 The respondent was also allowed to indicate if he or she did not know the
 correct answer.
 The household was considered knowledgeable on a particular topic if at
 least one of the spouses indicated a correct answer.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first question was related to planting.
 In our video, we recommended a spacing of 75cm x 30cm with 1 plant per
 hill, and this was the correct option.
 Other possible answers included a spacing of 75cm x 60cm with two plants
 per hill, which is standard for many farmers and recommended by many agricultur
al extension agents, and an intermediate alternative of 75cm x 30cm with
 2 seeds per hill.
 Because our video recommended a technique that deviates from what is assumed
 to be standard spacing, we assume that the recommended practice is new
 to most of the farmers.
 The second question is less related to technical knowledge, but more to
 viewing farming as a business.
 In the video, we paid ample attention to promoting an approach where farmers
 start small and grow over time by reinvesting, and we emphasized the benefits
 of combining inputs rather than investing only in e.g., improved seed.
 We want to see if farmers internalize this advice and ask what a successful
 farmer would do if he or she only has 40,000 shillings.
 The correct answer is to use this sum to purchased improved seed and fertilizer
 and start intensified farming on a small area.
 Alternative options were to: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

use all the money to buy hybrid seeds, because without good seeds, yields
