\begin_layout Section*
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a world characterized by incomplete and asymmetric information, and intra-hou
sehold gender related constraints to efficiency, targeted efforts to fill
 knowledge gaps can make a big difference 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "banerjee2011poor,udry1996gender"

\end_inset

.
 However, not every information campaign is equally effective nor inclusive,
 and often, seemingly small attributes, such as the way it is delivered,
 who is targeted by the message and who delivers the message, can result
 in significant differences in impact at the household and intra-household
 level.
 Understanding and quantifying the importance of each of these design attributes
 through rigorous evaluation research should therefore be an essential part
 of any knowledge exchange model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Motivated by the observation that most agricultural extension advisory services
 are biased toward men, this study assesses the impact of two gender-related
 attributes of a generic agricultural extension information campaign.
 The first attribute is related to the gender of the person (or gender compositi
on of the persons) that provide the information.
 The second attribute pertains to the gender of the person (or gender compositio
n of the persons) to whom the information is targeted.
 Taken together, these two attributes enable us to test various of hypotheses
 toughing upon intra-household information asymmetries and bargaining power,
 cooperative approaches to farming, gender stereotypes in agriculture, and
 gender homophily effects in extension advisory systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The various hypotheses are tested using a field experiment where the messenger
 of the information and the recipient of the information is randomly altered
 according to a 3 by 3 factorial design.
 The study population was maize farm households in Eastern Uganda, from
 which we sampled about 3,600 couples.
 These farmers were shown a video according to the treatment group they
 were randomly assigned to.
 The videos showed how modern technologies and improved agronomic practices
 can be used to increase production.
 The messages were packaged in an attractive and accessible manner, and
 featured role-model farmers explaining how intensification of maize production
 improved their lives.
 The videos were shown twice, once just before the planting season, and
 once during planting stage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We first checked if the information intervention works, by comparing household
 level outcomes of households that were shown the agricultural extension
 information video to outcomes of households that were allocated to a placebo
 treatment.
 We found that as a result of being shown the video, farmers had experienced
 improvements in several key knowledge outcomes.
 As a result of being shown the video, farmers also adopted a range of recommend
ed practices.
 As a result of having been shown a video, households reduced the area under
 maize cultivation while producing the same amount, leading to a significant
 increase in maize yields, from 428 kg/acre to 488 kg/acre.
 We found no effect on self-assessed well-being, nor on consumption expenditures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We then turned to the analysis of the gender attributes.
 We found that reducing information asymmetries, by making sure both household
 co-heads receive the same information, did not affect knowledge, indicating
 information was to some extent shared between spouses.
 We also found targeting both spouses in information campaigns increased
 joint decision making, joint adoption and joint production.
 Furthermore, we found that arming women with information led to increased
 knowledge of women, more decision-making by women and more adoption under
 female management than when information is targeted to the man only within
 the household.
 However, we did not find an impact on production under female management,
 suggesting women are constrained by production factors other than only
 knowledge.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also test if priming a cooperative approach to farming encourages spouses
 to work more together.
 We find that showing a video where a couple explains how to be a successful
 maize farmer indeed leads spouses to increase joint decision making and
 joint adoption.
 We also attempted to challenge the prevailing view that maize farming is
 a male business by showing videos that involve women in maize farming.
 We found that this reduced the likelihood that men decided, and adopt,
 unilaterally.
 Finally, we found that homophily effects related to gender seem to exist
 in agricultural extension as women tended to adopt more modern technologies
 and practices on their plots when they were informed by a fellow woman.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our study thus showed that a low cost, scalable agricultural information
 campaign using video can have an important effect on knowledge, adoption
 behavior and farm management, and ultimately production.
 It further underscores the importance of paying close attention to the
 various design features of such an information campaign.
 We looked at the importance of only two gender related features (messenger
 and recipient) and found this to be relevant for effectiveness and inclusivity.
 This finding thus suggest other design features may be equally, if not
 more important.
 Therefore, future research on other design features, such as the effect
 of the way the information is packaged or framed, may provide invaluable
 in designing effective and inclusive agricultural extension advisory services.
\end_layout

